In [115]:
%matplotlib inline
import pylab as plt
import nibabel as nb
plt.plot(nb.load(func_file).get_fdata()[32, 32, 15, :]);

In this figure above, we see that at the very beginning there are extreme values, which hint to the fact that steady state was not reached yet. Therefore, we want to exclude the dummy scans from the original data. This can be achieved with FSL's ExtractROI

In [116]:
from nipype.interfaces.fsl import ExtractROI
In [117]:
extract = Node(ExtractROI(t_min=4, t_size=-1, output_type='NIFTI'), name="extract")

This ExtractROI node can now be connected to the gunzip_func node from above. To do this, we use the following command:

In [118]:
preproc.connect([(gunzip_func, # The source node object
                  extract, # The destination node object
                  [('out_file', # The name of the output field from the source node
                    'in_file' )])]) # The name of the input field from the destination node
connect([(source, dest, [("source_output1", "dest_input1")])]) # Code format used above

Compute Coregistration Matrix¶

As a next step, we will make sure that the functional images are coregistered to the anatomical image. For this, we will use FSL's FLIRT function. As we just created a white matter probability map, we can use this together with the a Boundary-Based Registration (BBR) cost function do optimize the image coregistration. As some helpful notes... use a degree of freedom of 6 specify the cost function as bbr use the schedule='/usr/share/fsl/5.0/etc/flirtsch/bbr.sch'

In [136]:
from nipype.interfaces.fsl import FLIRT
In [137]:
# Initiate FLIRT node here
In [138]:
coreg = Node(FLIRT(dof=6,
                   cost='bbr',
                   schedule='/usr/local/fsl/etc/flirtsch/bbr.sch',
                   output_type='NIFTI'),
             name="coreg")
In [139]:
# Connect FLIRT node to the other nodes here
In [140]:
preproc.connect([(gunzip_anat, coreg, [('out_file', 'reference')]), 
                 (mcflirt, coreg, [('mean_img', 'in_file')])
])
connect([(source, dest, [("source_output1", "dest_input1"), ("source_output2", "dest_input2") ]) ])
In [141]:
from nipype.interfaces.fsl import Threshold

# Threshold - Threshold WM probability image
threshold_WM = Node(Threshold(thresh=0.5,
                              args='-bin',
                              output_type='NIFTI'),
                name="threshold_WM")
In [142]:
# Select WM segmentation file from segmentation output
def get_wm(files):
    return files[1][0]

# Connecting the segmentation node with the threshold node
preproc.connect([(segment, threshold_WM, [(('native_class_images', get_wm),
                                           'in_file')])])
In [143]:
preproc.connect([(threshold_WM, coreg, [('out_file', 'wm_seg')])])

Apply Coregistration Matrix to functional image¶

In [144]:
# Specify the isometric voxel resolution you want after coregistration
desired_voxel_iso = 4

# Apply coregistration warp to functional images
applywarp = Node(FLIRT(interp='spline',
                       apply_isoxfm=desired_voxel_iso,
                       output_type='NIFTI'),
                 name="applywarp")
In [145]:
# Connecting the ApplyWarp node to all the other nodes
preproc.connect([(mcflirt, applywarp, [('out_file', 'in_file')]),
                 (coreg, applywarp, [('out_matrix_file', 'in_matrix_file')]),
                 (gunzip_anat, applywarp, [('out_file', 'reference')])
                 ])

Data output with DataSink¶

We don't need all those temporary files. So let's use Datasink to keep only those files that we actually need for the 1st and 2nd level analysis.

In [186]:
from nipype.interfaces.io import DataSink

# Initiate the datasink node
output_folder = 'datasink_handson'
datasink = Node(DataSink(base_directory='/Users/hanningsu/Desktop/Nipype_Tutorial/hands_on_preprocessing/output/',
                         container=output_folder),
                name="datasink")

We keep:

from the artifact detection node the outlier file as well as the outlier plot

from the motion correction node the motion parameters

from the last node, the detrended functional image

In [187]:
# Connect nodes to datasink here
preproc.connect([(art, datasink, [('outlier_files', 'preproc.@outlier_files'),
                                  ('plot_files', 'preproc.@plot_files')]),
                 (mcflirt, datasink, [('par_file', 'preproc.@par')]),
                 (detrend, datasink, [('detrended_file', 'preproc.@func')]),
                 ])

There are many unnecessary file specifiers that we can get rid off. To do so, we can use DataSink's substitutions parameter. For this, we create a list of tuples: on the left, we specify the string that we want to replace and on the right, with what we want to replace it with.

In [190]:
## Use the following substitutions for the DataSink output
substitutions = [('asub', 'sub'),
                 ('_ses-test_task-fingerfootlips_bold_roi_mcf', ''),
                 ('.nii.gz.par', '.par'),
                 ]

# To get rid of the folder '_subject_id_07' and renaming detrend
substitutions += [('_subject_id_%s/detrend' % s,
                   '_subject_id_%s/sub-%s_detrend' % (s, s)) for s in subject_list]
substitutions += [('_subject_id_%s/' % s, '') for s in subject_list]
datasink.inputs.substitutions = substitutions
